From 16de4f1bd837561a302c158b03871cf3d647e63e Mon Sep 17 00:00:00 2001
From: Faisal Khan <mfkhan@sofi.org>
Date: Sun, 26 Apr 2026 21:32:28 -0700
Subject: [PATCH 5/7] fix(layout): centre collapsed sidebar footer buttons and
 align mobile heading anchors
MIME-Version: 1.0
Content-Type: text/plain; charset=UTF-8
Content-Transfer-Encoding: 8bit

Two related layout fixes for the same kind of bug — a child element rendering
correctly relative to its parent's coordinate system but landing in the wrong
place inside the visible viewport.

1. Sidebar collapsed footer buttons (continuation of c6a0246a). Moving the
   buttons inside the rail wasn't enough to centre them on the rail
   centerline: with .sidebar-footer's `transform-origin: left center` the
   composed host+footer scales collapse to identity, so the footer's interior
   coordinates map straight to viewport coordinates and a button anchored
   via padding-left landed at viewport x=36 instead of x=30.

   Move .sidebar-footer into the same `transform-origin: center center`
   group as .sidebar-header. With mismatched origins (host at x=0, footer
   at x=130 = --sidebar-width / 2) the composition becomes a translation
   `viewport x = footer-local x − 100`. Add `display: flex;
   flex-direction: column; align-items: center` so the 40 px buttons
   centre at footer-local x=130, mapping to viewport x=30 — the same
   trick that already centres the avatar.

   Only .nav-list stays in the `left center` group, because
   .nav-list::before (the active-item indicator) is anchored at left: 0
   and needs to stay pinned to the rail's left edge. The counter-transform
   comment is rewritten to spell out the two groups and the mismatched-
   origin translation that drives the centring.

2. Mobile heading permalink anchor. The desktop rule sizes the anchor at
   `height: 1lh` so its `align-items: center` lands the icon on the
   line's vertical midline while it's absolutely positioned in the
   gutter. The mobile @media block flips the anchor to `position: static`
   but never resets the height, so the inline-flex anchor (with no text
   content) used its bottom edge as its baseline, aligned that with the
   heading text baseline, and ended up reaching ~14 px above the
   line-box top — pushing the centred 16 px icon to render visibly
   above the heading text instead of on it.

   Reset `height: auto` on the mobile rule so the inline-flex sizes to
   the 16 px SVG, and add `vertical-align: middle` so the icon centre
   aligns with the parent text's optical middle. Desktop is unaffected.

Verification: npm run lint, sidebar.component.spec (12), and
markdown.service.spec (16) all green. No HTML output changes, so no
spec edits were needed.

